<paragraph blockId="9.[189,754,337,359]" box="[189,754,337,359]" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">
<heading box="[189,754,337,359]" centered="true" fontSize="9" level="2" pageId="9" pageNumber="706" reason="2">
<taxonomicName authority="(TOWNSEND, 1898)" baseAuthorityName="Townsend" baseAuthorityYear="1898" box="[189,754,337,359]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="706" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tamaulipanum">
<emphasis box="[189,526,337,358]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">COPESTYLUM TAMAULIPANUM</emphasis>
(TOWNSEND, 1898)
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[164,779,375,611]" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">
<emphasis box="[164,428,375,397]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">Larva and puparium:</emphasis>
Anterior fold without extra large spicules. Anterior spiracles with three openings. Abdominal vestiture of short, upright setae. Anal lobe without spicules. Posterior breathing tube orange, tapering. AP smooth, shiny and as long as TR is wide. Pupal spiracles orange, matt, and with three encircling rings of openings in upper third. Pupal spiracles as wide apart as a pupal spiracle is long.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="706" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[164,779,654,859]" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">
<emphasis box="[164,687,654,675]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">
Taxonomic notes: 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Townsend" baseAuthorityYear="1898" box="[373,687,654,675]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="706" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tamaulipanum">Copestylum tamaulipanum</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[297,443,684,706]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="706" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alberlena">
<emphasis box="[297,443,684,706]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">C. alberlena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Marcos-García &amp; Hancock &amp; Pérez-Bañón &amp; Maier" authorityYear="2009" box="[516,740,684,706]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="706" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="multipunctatum">
<emphasis box="[516,740,684,706]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">C. multipunctatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a tapering posterior breathing tube and light orange pupal spiracles. It differs from both these species in the AP that is as long as the TR is wide. In the latter two species the AP is shorter than the TR is wide.
</paragraph>
